Convert dteday to month_name column

df$dteday <- ymd(df$dteday)
df$month_name <- as.character(month(df$dteday, label = TRUE))

Simple Linear Regression cnt (dep) & month_name (indep)

model1 <- lm(cnt ~ month_name, data = df)
summary(model1)

The R Squared value is 0.3906 or 39.06% of the variation in cnt explained by month_name. And the adjusted R Squared is 38.1% which shows that the fitted values are below the actual values of 39.06%. This shows a positive correlation & also show less variation in the regression model meaning less variation in dependent variable explained by indep variable. Also the P-Value is small showing more statistical confidence in the model.

Predict which month set as reference and cnt (April is Reference)

ggplot(model1, aes(x = month_name, y = cnt)) +
  geom_point() +
  expand_limits(x = c(0,1)) +
  stat_smooth(method = 'lm', fullrange = T)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

newObservations <- data.frame(month_name = 'Apr'
                              , cnt = c(2000, 3000, 4000) )

newObservations$predictedCnt = predict(model1, newObservations)

As shown in the summary of Model1, April is set as the reference month. The predicted count for April would be, cnt = 4484.9

***Explain why the R-squared is different from the two simple regression models

Model2 is different from Model1 due to adding in the temp into the Linear Regression Model. Since temp has a higher coefficient meaning higher correlation, the R squared value is a little bit higher than the R squared in Model1.

***Compare the coefficient estimates for the month_nameJan variable in Model1 and Model2.

With regular text explain why the coefficient estimates are different. Model1 Jan Coefficient is -2308.6 while Model2 Jan coeff is -852.31. They are different because when adding in the Temp variable, the correlation increases which is shown by the increase in R squared causing a better correlation in Model2 Jan coeff.
